# Preferences: minimal overrides only

## Rule
- A DI `<preference>` replaces the **entire class type** in the object manager.
- When a preference is required (for example to alter private/protected behavior), the preference class must **extend the original** and **override only the minimal methods needed**.
- **Do not copy/paste the full original class** into `app/code/`. This makes upgrades harder and diverges from upstream fixes.
- **Only remove “identical” methods if the preference class extends the original.** If it does **not** extend the original, removing identical methods can break required behavior or interface/contract expectations.

## Guidance
- Prefer plugins (`before/after/around`) when possible.
- If a preference is unavoidable, keep the constructor aligned and call `parent::__construct(...)`.
- If a preference cannot extend the original (rare), treat it as a full replacement and keep all required methods, even if identical.
